caption: Great service, unfortunately the food was average which was somewhat disappointing. We came for the pasta; ordered the Busiati short rib bolognese which lacked depth of flavour but the meat was tender & the Cavatelli with sausage & browned sage butter, the cavatelli itself was delicious but again no real flavours from the sage or sausage. The special Italian salad with anchovy dressing was the star of the show, so to speak. Great friendly attentive service, wish we went to F&F for pizza instead.

All around meh. Waiters fine but brusque. Pasta is nice but other dishes were very poor. Tables set around a large waiters’ station, stacked baby chairs and a disused bar made it feel like we were eating in back-of-house.

Being married to a real Italian has spoiled me. Apps and tiramisu were the best part. My bolognese was lackluster, tasteless and the pasta was over cooked. It was my second time here after two years. I can’t give it a third try. Nope.

Food is a hit or a miss. It was nice that they accommodated us without a reservation. The lemon pasta should be removed from the menu. I would equate the dish to undercooked ramen noodles dressed lemon Lysol. The ricotta lasagna was tasty. Disappointed in the dessert. We went with the chocolate tart to share and it was about the size of an Oreo cookie. The price doesn’t justify the quality of food. Side note I found it odd that our server requested we wear a mask whenever she walked by, but later was hanging out at a table of unmasked patrons and didn’t make the same request. Made us feel weird. I won’t return based on the food.

So many favorites on the menu that it’s hard to decide (went with Lasagna tonight - pictured). Do not pass go, do not collect $200 and just pull up to one of the three Fs and you’ll be happy you did.

Unfortunately I cannot recommend Frankies to anyone given their response to the COVID-19 pandemic. We had to cancel our wedding scheduled for June 20, 2020 due to the shutdown and circumstances in NYC for restaurants/events and also the limitations on gatherings over 10 people. I provided written cancellation to them in accordance with my contract on March 16, 2020. The deposit is fully refundable so long as at least 28 days notice is provided. This is per the contract I signed, as well as Frankies. They confirmed via email my deposit would be fully refunded to me within 30 days. The next day I received an email saying my deposit couldn't be refunded until the restaurant "re-opened." As we all know, restaurants are no where close to re-opening for in person dining, which would have been (potentially) when I could have received my $14,200 deposit back. I went back and forth with their COO Lauren Merkin all throughout March and April regarding my deposit and I even offered her a payment plan. While I tried to be understanding of their small business, they unfortunately did not work with me whatsoever to get me my money back. I offered her an option to pay me only $5,000 within the 30 day time frame and then pay me $2,000 a month thereafter- which I think is extremely generous of me to offer when I never agreed to give Frankies an interest free loan. They had no idea what my financial situation was and basically fraudulently took my MUCH NEEDED $14,200 after I did not receive a check on April 15th. Lauren told me they didn't have the money to give me. Very scary to think a restaurant that holds events spends your money as soon as it is received. They do NOT hold your event money in escrow for safe keeping until AFTER the event concludes. Luckily I was extremely fortunate to have used my Chase Freedom credit card to charge all of the deposits totaling $14,200. I reported Frankies as fraudulent on April 15th and Chase refunded me the money immediately. I just received word yesterday that (of course) I won my dispute and the refund is now permanent on my account. I feel incredibly sad thinking of all the couples who may have paid in cash or by check that aren't as lucky as me.  Frankies looked like a beautiful space to hold an intimate wedding and the pasta was incredible. However, given the extreme uncertainty going forward for likely many years due to this pandemic, I can never recommend Frankies to anyone holding an event.

Returned to Frankies today at lunch around 3:30pm.  There are 4 people sitting in the bar and I asked if they were still serving food.  The bartender said yes and I asked to sit down at the bar or side bar tables.  She stated that they don't serve food in the front at this time and that I had to sit in the back dining room.  Fine.  I sit in the back, there was a single occupied table only 2 persons.  Every table was empty.   I wanted to check some email on my laptop and was told that was not allowed.   No electronics were allowed on the table.   As this was the purpose of my late lunch, I started to leave.  The bartender that helped me earlier thought it was strange that I was leaving and I explained that I was told that I could not use my laptop at the table.  She stated, did the manager tell you that?  I said I am not sure who she was, but I thought it was my server.  She explained that "well, its not that type of a restaurant".  I said there is no one here and its not like I came at prime dinner hours, it was 3:30 in the afternoon and they had no business.  She shrugged her shoulders that was that.  The ownership and staff at Frankies 457 has seriously lost their way and completely tossed any ideas of hospitality out the window.

Don’t bother going unless you have a lot of time. The place has one loo, and a tiny kitchen compared to the space they have so service is obviously terribly slow. So slow in fact that a friend on our table had to leave without eating on a 2 hour journey back home. To top it off, the staff have the audacity to demand a gratuity which isn’t an entitlement. It’s given if the customers feel it’s worth it. We have all worked in restaurants and know when it’s due and are religious about giving it when deserved but this place just ruined our evening. The bean soup was awful as well, bland and tiny portion sizes. Not going back.

Easily one of the best Italian restaurants I've ever at.  Intimate (read: small) place and very popular so they fill up fast.  We put our name on the list for first available (bar or table) and went 2 blocks down the street to Abilene for drinks while we waited.  Once I got a call we had 2 seats waiting for us at the bar.  Service was spectacular.  We went with the bartender's suggestion for our appetizer, a burrata special, which was delicious.  My wife had the sweet potato sage ravioli, I opted for the short rib over polenta.  Both were outstanding.  We of course had the tiramisu for dessert.  We happened upon Frankies by accident and cannot believe our good fortune.  We will be back.
